**David Hildebrand Wilson** (born 1948) is an American businessman, experimental animator, and co‑founder of the enigmatic **[Museum of Jurassic Technology](/Museum_of_Jurassic_Technology)** in **[Los Angeles, California](/Los_Angeles,_California)**.  He is best known for turning the act of curating the inexplicable into a full‑time vocation, a pursuit that has earned him both a MacArthur “genius” grant and a reputation for delighting in the absurd.

Wilson entered the world of art and science with the sort of restless curiosity that would later make him a museum‑maker of note.  After graduating from high school he enrolled at **[Kalamazoo College](/Kalamazoo_College)**, where he majored in **urban entomology** with a minor in art—a combination that sounds like a joke until you realize he actually spent years studying the hidden lives of insects while sketching their forms.  He would later trade campus labs for the more colorful chaos of the **[California Institute of the Arts](/California_Institute_of_the_Arts)**, earning an MFA in **Experimental Animation** in 1976.  The move from entomology to animation may seem like a pivot, but for Wilson it was merely a change of canvas; the same obsessive eye that tracked beetle wings now tracked the movement of drawn frames.

His professional trajectory took a decisive turn when he and his wife, Diana Wilson, decided to create a space that would **re‑define the museum** itself.  The result was the **[Museum of Jurassic Technology](/Museum_of_Jurassic_Technology)**, a venue that pretends to showcase extinct creatures while actually questioning what a museum can be.  The institution’s very name is a tongue‑in‑cheek nod to the **Jurassic** period, yet its exhibits include everything from miniature micromosaics to alleged “living fossils” that blur the line between fact and folklore.  Visitors often leave bewildered, unsure whether they have toured a legitimate scientific collection or an elaborate performance art piece.  Wilson himself has described the museum as “a place where the truth is optional and the wonder is mandatory.”

Wilson’s contributions have not gone unnoticed by the broader cultural establishment.  In **2001** he was awarded the prestigious **[MacArthur Fellowship](/MacArthur_Fellows_Program)**, often called the “genius grant,” a prize that comes with an unrestricted cash stipend and the kind of validation that makes even the most skeptical curators sit up straight.  The same year he also received the **[Creative Capital](/Creative_Capital)** **Moving Image Award**, a testament to his experimental film work that continues to influence contemporary visual storytelling.  His life and the museum’s oddities have been chronicled in the book **“**[Mr. Wilson's Cabinet of Wonder](/Mr._Wilson%27s_Cabinet_of_Wonder)**”** (1995), a text that blends scholarly analysis with a dash of playful sarcasm—precisely the tone Wilson seems to enjoy when he’s not busy convincing people that a taxidermied squirrel can be a work of art.

Beyond the awards, Wilson’s public engagements reveal a man who is as comfortable delivering a dead‑pan lecture as he is arranging a display of “microscopic” sculptures that are, in reality, larger than life.  He has participated in panels such as “**[Wilson and Wilson: A Dialogue on Museums](/Template:Authority_control])**” at the USC Fisher Museum of Art, where he dissected the paradoxes of museum ethics with the same dry humor he uses when describing a beetle’s mating ritual.  His interview with **NPR** in October 2001, titled “**[Artist Projects – Levsha (The Art of the Microminiature)]**,” showcased his fascination with the tiny, a theme that recurs throughout his curatorial decisions.

The impact of Wilson’s work extends beyond the walls of his Los Angeles museum; it reverberates through academic circles, popular culture, and the occasional viral internet meme that asks, “What if a museum could be a joke?”  Scholars cite his approach in discussions of **museum studies**, while journalists reference his methods when exploring the boundaries of public education.  Yet, for all his public visibility, Wilson remains a figure who prefers the shadows of his own making—an ironic stance for someone who has built an entire institution predicated on being seen.

